<doc id="850948" wikidata="Q5505362" url="?curid=850948" title="From Beirut to Jerusalem">
<text>From Beirut to Jerusalem (1989) is a book by American journalist Thomas L. Friedman chronicling his days as a reporter in Beirut during the Lebanese Civil War and in Jerusalem through the first year of the Intifada. 

Friedman wrote a 17-page epilogue for the first paperback edition (Anchor Books, 1990) concerning the potential for peaceful resolution in Israel and Palestine.

==Reception==

It received the 1989 National Book Award for Nonfiction and also the Cornelius Ryan Award. In a book review for &quot;The Village Voice&quot;, Edward Said criticized what he saw as a naive, arrogant, and orientalist account of the Israel–Palestine conflict.

